'''Perfluoropolyether''' ('''PFPE''') is a type of liquid lubricant used in the Aerospace industry for over 30 years.<ref>{{cite web |title=Spontaneous Dewetting of a Perfluoropolyether |publisher=[[National Aeronautics and Space Administration]] |author=Bradley Shogrin |date=August 1995 |url=https://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/19950026498.pdf |accessdate=November 29, 2017}}</ref> The main properties of PFPE are being temperature resistant between 215 K - 530 K (depending on specific composites), having very low outgassing compared to other fluids ([[vapor pressure|vapour pressure]] of 6e-8 torr) and having a dielectric strength of around 15.7 MV/m.<ref>http://www.solvay.com/en/markets-and-products/featured-products/Fomblin-PFPE-Lubricants.html</ref>

