{{Chem-stub}}

{{thermodynamics|cTopic=Processes and Cycles}} Elliott J. Stoddard invented and patented two versions of the '''Stoddard engine''', the first in 1919 and the second in 1933. The general engine classification is an [[external combustion engine]] with [[valves]] and single-phase [[gaseous]] working fluid (i.e. a "hot air engine"). The internal [[working fluid]] was originally [[air]], although in modern versions, other gases such as [[helium]] or [[hydrogen]] may be used.
One potential [[thermodynamics|thermodynamic]] advantage of using valves is to minimize the adverse effects of "unswept volume" in the [[heat exchangers]] (sometimes called "dead volume"), which is known to reduce engine efficiency and power output in the valveless [[Stirling engine]].
==The 1919 Stoddard engine== The generalized thermodynamic processes of the 1919 Stoddard cycle are:<ref name="patent1919">[https://www.google.com/patents/US1306865 1919 Stoddard Engine US Patent]</ref> # [[Adiabatic process|Adiabatic]] [[Compression ratio|compression]] # [[Isobaric process|Isobaric]] heat-addition # Adiabatic [[Thermal expansion|expansion]] # Isobaric heat-removal
The engine design in the patent was using a [[scotch yoke]].
==The 1933 Stoddard engine== In the 1933 design,<ref name="patent1933">[https://www.google.com/patents/US1926463 1933 Stoddard Engine US Patent]</ref> Stoddard reduced the internal volume of the [[heat exchanger]]s maintaining the same generalized thermodynamic processes as the 1919 cycle.
==Gallery== {{Gallery | title = Stoddard engine diagrams | lines = 2 | width = 330 | height = 450 |File:StoddardEnginePatentDrawing1919.jpg|The 1919 Stoddard Engine |File:Stoddard1933 fig2.PNG|The 1933 Stoddard Engine }}
